[x] decide whether the formatter should own horizontal (intra-line) spacing $ RESOLVED 2026-07-03: the topiary query was never the real bug. patterns.js's safe_text/tag_text (name, story, tags, predecessor names) used notChars(), a greedy regex that doesn't exclude the space character, so tree-sitter's maximal-munch tokenizer silently absorbed leading/trailing whitespace INTO the token's own byte range whenever it bordered a metadata sigil. Fields with strict patterns (priority_level, datetime, uuid) never did this, which is exactly why doubling was inconsistent -- it tracked which token type preceded the boundary, not which topiary rule fired. Fix: added notCharsTrimmed() in patterns.js, a start/end-anchored variant that still allows interior spaces (multi-word names/tags untouched) but never lets a token absorb a leading or trailing run of whitespace. With that invariant, formatting.scm now uses two blanket rules -- (_ name: (_) @prepend_space) and (_ metadata: (_) @prepend_space) -- covering every state->name and field->field boundary with exactly one space, unconditionally. Icon->value spacing within a single field (!1, #uuid, *StoryName) stays zero-space by the existing compact convention; that was never the bug. Verified via a new idempotency test (format(format(x)) == format(x)) in clearhead-core, plus manual round-trips of with_everything.actions through `clearhead format file` run twice with a diff. Full clearhead-core and clearhead-cli suites pass (only the two pre-existing, unrelated --format json failures remain). Original investigation notes: horizontal gaps around !priority, +tags, and other single-line metadata sigils were silently stripped to zero on any write that reformats the line, since topiary drops unlisted inter-token whitespace by default; adding @prepend_space per missing field produced inconsistent doubling depending on node adjacency, which sent the investigation upstream into the grammar itself. See also platform trust charter's round-trip property test action -- same underlying bug class (2026-07-02 multi-tag data loss). $ !2 %2026-07-03T09:50 #019f28c7-c3e8-7ee2-87e4-ba8cd020da43
